post_text:
Greetings Nova Families,

These have been difficult times. COVID-19 has presented persistent challenges for students, teachers, staff and the community as we attempt to navigate through one of the most complex crises to face the business of education. We believe that the best way to work through a crisis is together – and together is how we will move forward as we plan to “Return to School.”

We have been faced with difficult decisions about what school will look like and how we will provide the best education for all students. When we return to school on September 8, 2020, our plan will begin with 100% virtual instruction through October 6, 2020. When it is safe, we will add in-person instruction. The Nova Academy Board of Trustees have agreed to follow the guidelines of Judge Clay Jenkins, health authorities and surrounding districts. We will keep you informed of changes along the way.

Thank you for your patience, commitment and partnership as we return to school for the 2020-2021 school year.

Sincerely,

Nova Academy

post_text:
Dear Parents/Guardians,

The Nova Academy Board of Trustees have agreed to follow the guidelines of Judge Clay Jenkins, health authorities and surrounding districts to delay the start of school until after Labor Day. Nova Academy will begin school on Tuesday, September 8, 2020, offering both virtual and face-to-face learning. Please note our new school hours are from 8:00 a.m.-3:00 p.m. This decision comes after weeks of conversations and collaboration regarding the pandemic and to ensure we are taking the proper safeguards towards ensuring a successful learning environment for all our students and staff.

We are committed to providing our students with a quality education during these uncertain times. Thank you for your patience and understanding as we continue to lead safely into the 2020-2021 school year.

Sincerely,
Nova Academy

post_text: Board meeting July 28, 2020
text: Board meeting July 28, 2020

post_text:
Greetings, Nova Parents, Students and Staff!

I hope this letter finds you and your family in the best of health during the pandemic. I appreciate your patience and understanding as we have been adjusting to the new normal, like you, to the drastic changes during the last few months of COVID -19. Recently, Judge Jenkins announced that schools will not re-open face to face until after Labor Day. I want you to know that our top priority is the safety and health of our students and staff as we plan to re-open for the 2020-2021 school year. Due to the wide spread of the coronavirus we will provide additional details after our next board meeting July 28, 2020. Thanks for your cooperation and understanding as continue to work together to ensure our students and staff are safe.

With Students in Mind,

Eureka S. Fordham, Superintendent

shared_text:
Nova Academy Cedar Hill, Prichard & Scyene
May 21 at 5:53 AM ·

As the COVID-19 pandemic is changing the way the world connects, celebrates and communicates, we want to share with you that together we can figure out how to move forward during these uncertain times.

Graduation may look different this year, but our commitment to Nova Academy graduates hasn’t wavered. Graduation is more than just a day, it’s honoring years of hard work and dedication. Graduation is celebrating how far our graduates have come and the excitement and endless possibilities of how far they can go. This milestone is worth sharing with everyone who has encouraged them, cheered them on since day one, and who has always believed in them.

So let's join together and celebrate them on Thursday, May 21, 2020 at 6:30 pm by watching a virtual graduation via our Nova Academy website: www.novaacademy.org

5th Grade: Roller Coaster Science Activity

Investigation: Observe how gravity affects marbles as they roll, and how would friction created by the sand affect the roll of the marble.

6th Grade: Roller Coaster Project

Purpose: This project allowed the students to demonstrate their knowledge of motion, energy, and forces, as well as other areas of physics that may apply in building roller coasters of card stock and paper.

• Be Strong!
• Be You!

post_text:
Hello Parents! (Prichard campus)

In, Writing this month, we are covering prefixes/suffixes, digraphs, three-letter blends, r-Controlled vowels; main idea and details, cause and effect, sequence, author’s purpose; idioms, context clues, and homophones.

In Science & Social Studies class, students have completed place value of whole numbers and decimals and now moving into addition and subtraction of whole numbers and decimals. We are looking forward to a great year!

Ms. Porter
Ms. Olorunnisomo
Ms. Boynick

post_text: George Washington Carver was an agricultural scientist and inventor who developed hundreds of products using peanuts (though not peanut butter, as is often claimed), sweet potatoes and soybeans. Born an African-American slave a year before the practice was outlawed, Carver left home at a young age to pursue education and would eventually earn a master’s degree in agricultural science from Iowa State University. He would go on to teach and conduct research at Tuskegee University for decades, and soon after his death his childhood home would be named a national monument — the first of its kind to honor an African American.
text: George Washington Carver was an agricultural scientist and inventor who developed hundreds of products using peanuts (though not peanut butter, as is often claimed), sweet potatoes and soybeans. Born an African-American slave a year before the practice was outlawed, Carver left home at a young age to pursue education and would eventually earn a master’s degree in agricultural science from Iowa State University. He would go on to teach and conduct research at Tuskegee University for decades, and soon after his death his childhood home would be named a national monument — the first of its kind to honor an African American.

post_text: First Woman Representative: Shirley Chisholm was the first African American woman elected to the House of Representatives. She was elected in 1968 and represented the state of New York. She broke ground again four years later in 1972 when she was the first major party African-American candidate and the first female candidate for president of the United States.

post_text: Black History Month: The celebration of Black History Month began as “Negro History Week,” which was created in 1926 by Carter G. Woodson, a noted African American historian, scholar, educator, and publisher. It became a month-long celebration in 1976. The month of February was chosen to coincide with the birthdays of Frederick Douglass and Abraham Lincoln.
